<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0211</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Federation of Small Businesses – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB is the UK’s leading business organisation. It exists to protect and promote the interests of the self-employed and all those who run their own business. The FSB is non-party political, and with around 200,000 members, it is also the largest organisation representing small and medium sized businesses in the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Small businesses make up 99.3 per cent of all businesses in the UK, and make a huge contribution to the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> UK economy.  They contribute 50</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">er cent of the GDP and employ 59</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> per cent of the private sector workforce. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB has an interest in a number of aspects of this Bill. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Specifically on the changes to a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprenticeship regulation, health and safe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ty and measures to introduce de</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">regulatory measures quickly.   </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">his brief does not cover all aspects of the draft Bill, only those that are pertinent to FSB members.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">FSB has welcomed </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the package of measures </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that this Government has made to improve the regulatory environment for small businesses. The FSB supports proportionate, risk-based, well evidenced and well considered regulation which is designed to suit the needs of small and micro businesses. The FSB wants to see further changes made to the institutional framework for regulatory reform to ensure that disproportionate, non-evidence based and unnecessary regulation is not brought forward. The FSB supports this Bill as a small part in a much wider package of measures to reduce the flow of new regulation and to deal with the existing stock. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Context</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Small businesses consistently mention regulation as a barrier to growth. In the last FSB quarterly report it was rated the 5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> biggest barrier to growth with only the economy, consumer demand, fuel prices and access to finance above it. Having said that, most businesses appreciate that proportionate, necessary regulation can support business growth and help to deal with rogue traders. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In a survey in November 2011, members said the following about regulation:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Forty-one per cent of members said that the cost of complying with regulation had increased, with only one per cent claiming that it had decreased</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Eighty-six per cent of businesses claimed that they had not experienced any positive improvements such as greater clarity of regulatory requirements</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Sixty-one per cent of members claiming a cost said that the cost of complying with regulation is more than £1,000 per year and 10 per cent said that it cost them more than £10,000 a year</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB Survey Panel results indicate that constant changes to regulation, both existing and new, is the most difficult aspect of regulation. Sixty-four per cent of members claim that this was the most challenging issue, with a further 55 per cent saying that it was the sheer time involved</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The overall aim of all regulators should be to facilitate compliant growth. Regulators should deal with rogue traders appropriately, provide up-to-date and clear guidance </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and support to businesses to help with compliance and deal with non-compliance in a proportionate and transparent way. Where businesses are non-compliant due to misunderstanding or because it’s a complex area, regulators should work with the business to help them to become compliant in a proportionate way. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 1 - </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Health and safety at work: general duty of self-employed persons</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB supports this proposal</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> in principle</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. The FSB believes that exempting the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sole traders </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">who pose no risk to others </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">could </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">potentially </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">reduce </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">some </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">burden</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> for some</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> sole traders</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We do acknowledge that this benefit </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">be limit</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ed in terms of a tangible reduction of actions undertaken by business</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This was something that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Lofstedt</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">review </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">highlighted. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It can also be assumed that sole traders working from home in a low-risk sector will also not be inspected</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> frequently</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">However,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> the FSB envisages that this change </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">will be one less </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">consideration </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that a start-up business has to think about and this is welcome. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> more significant</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> benefit is the message that it send</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> about how health and safety regulation operates in the UK. It is sensible and proportionate that health and safety regulations are applied on a risk-based approach</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and appropriately applied</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.  Where a sole trader</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, whose business </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">activities in no way affect</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> other people, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">operates in a low-risk environment</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> undertaking low-risk work</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, it is proportionate to reduce the amount of compliance that they have to deal with. If businesses see health and safety regulation as sensible and proportionate </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it will be held in greater esteem. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This approach can be seen elsewhere in the EU. As </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Lofstedt</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> commented:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“EU legislation does not generally apply to the self-employed, and the approach by other member states varies, with some countries choosing not to apply health and safety law to the self-employed, whilst several apply the law to the self-employed only where activities are considered particularly hazardous or if they present risks to others. For example, in Sweden the self-employed are only covered in relation to chemicals and machinery to protect their safety and that of those who may be affected by their work, whilst in Germany the law does not apply to the self-employed except where their work may affect the safety of employees.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">He goes on to argue:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There is a case for following a similar approach to other countries and exempting from health and safety law those self-employed people (i.e. those who do not have any employees) whose workplace activities pose no potential risk of harm to others. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This would benefit approximately 1 million people. The actual burden that the regulations currently place upon these self-employed may not be particularly significant due to existing exceptions in some regulations</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and the limited prospect of these being enforced but it will help reduce the perception that health and safety law is inappropriately applied. This will complement HSE’s recently revised guidance for employers on </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">homeworkers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB agrees that this change must be simple to understand and use. If the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">legislation and the related guidance (which is more important for small businesses in many ways) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">too complicated with too many caveats for sole traders to be able to use effectively, then </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">this change will not be a simplification for small businesses. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">For this reason, until we see the draft guidance for this power, and what this regulatory change will mean for sole traders in practice, we will await full judgement. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The g</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">uidance must provide certainty for sole traders. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">However, we do support the principle.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 2 - </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Removal of employment tribunal</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s power to make wider recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB welcomes clause 2 to remove an Employment Tribunal’s power to make wider recommendations beyond the issue raised in the case. While Tribunals can be important learning experience for respondents, the Judiciary’s role is to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">apply the law to an historical situation and administer justice where appropriate to a claimant. Anything beyond this is arguably unnecessary and may even be construed as prejudicial to the interests of the employer.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> However, we do not anticipate the tangible effect of this change to be significant, as we understand that this power is rarely used.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> We would also note that the Government is moving in the opposite direction in relation to pay discrimination cases, whereby Judges will be able to require employers to undertake an Equal Pay Audit.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 3 - </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">English apprenticeships: simplification</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB understands that the basis for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">these changes </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is to remove existing legislation to clear the way for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">recommendations </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tha</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">t will come as a result of the Richard R</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">eview of Apprenticeships. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Independent Richard R</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">eview</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> of Apprenticeships</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">While t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">he FSB supports the vision of the Richard review which seeks to improve the quality and the reputation of Apprenticeships in England</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, we do urge caution and care to be taken in regards to implementation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB also believes that a phased approach is sensible so that too many big changes are made in one go. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">hile the FSB supports the principle of employers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> being put in control of the funding</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, we are concerned about the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> proposals as they currently stand</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. Sm</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">all businesses cannot absorb a significant or sudden </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">increase in the cost of Apprenticeships</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and will suffer cash flow difficulties if there are required to pay the full cost of the external training upfront before they receive the Government contribution</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> – this will put them off engaging.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Businesses sho</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">uld be at the heart of the a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprenticeship system and it should be a high quality course which sets young people </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">- and some older people entering new jobs - </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">up for a career. The FSB looks forward to working with Government on the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">next stages of the reforms and is keen to ensure that it works for small as well as large businesses as this is where </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprenticeship growth will come from.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Specifics of this Bill</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There is a need to ensure that these deregulatory changes do not have unintended consequences. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ny significant changes that come as a result of this Bill need to be piloted. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Transition arrangements need to be considered. Any potential for uncertainty will put small businesses off engaging. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Careful consideration also needs to be made about what these changes mean for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employers </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and young people across the whole UK. It is important that an Apprenticeship is transferable across borders. However, England does support the vision of the Richard review and believes that there needs to be scope for innovation in this area.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This Bill allows for the Secretary of State to revoke </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Apprenticeships</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> standards should they lose their credibility. Careful </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">thought</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> needs to be done about </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">businesses</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> that are partway through Apprenticeships at the point where </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">standards</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> are revoked. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB would like further explanation ab</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">out what is meant in A6 sections 2 and 3 where the Bill states that when an agreement no longer satisfies the stated conditions, the person for whom the apprentice is working must give the Apprentice written notice. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Employment law and Apprenticeships</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There is a need however, to ensure that this Bill continues to support and in fact </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">strengthen the message that an a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprentice is an employee and has no rights beyond those of other employees</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We understand from</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Abbey Legal Services</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">- the company that provides employment law support to FSB members - that there is an issue of clarity a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">round the employment status of a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprentices.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">They tell us that in order for Section 35 of Apprenticeships, Skills, Children and Learning Act 2009 (ASCLA) to apply there is a need to ensure that any agreement complies with Section 32.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n practice the problem arises where it is not clear whether an agreement fit</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> all the criteria listed within Section 32 of the Act or whether the absence of one of the criteria would be enough to bring it outside of Section 35.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> If </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is not clear then many lawyers will be advising their clients to err on the side of caution when it comes to terminating any contract of apprenticeship – unless and until case law develops to address these issues.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In addition to clarification on the above Act, they also tell us that it would be useful for it to be made clear that ‘if you employ an apprentice under this scheme then they </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">are treated as an employee and afforded no more, or less, rights than any other employee’.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Potentially, this may be something that would be placed in a statutory guidance document</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Statutory would be preferable to non-statutory. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The small business owner is much more likely to read a document designed to give them basic and clear guidance rather than look into the legislation behind it so not only would this provide the clarification required by any legal advisor but would also provide clearer guidance to the employer looking to employ an apprentice under this scheme</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">With this advice in mind, the FSB would urge Government and Parliament to use this Bill as an opportunity to provide clarity around the employment law status</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> of a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprentices and its implicati</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ons. The policy argument about a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprentices as employees has already been won – this was the aim of the 2009 ASCLA – but</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">wasn't</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">fully achieved. We know that clarity around this difficult issue will provide certainty to small businesses and hopefully this will incre</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ase their willingness to offer a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pprenticeship places</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses 50-57 </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> no longer of practical use </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">While the FSB supports the principle of a mechanism that can be used to remove obsolete legislation from the statute book, we believe that the current clauses are drafted far too broadly. We accept that the intention of these Clauses is to allow only legislation which no longer has an effect to be repealed using this mechanism, but we do not believe that this is reflected by the definition within the Bill. In particular we are concerned that the phrase “if the Minister considers that it is no longer of practical use” in Clause 51 could be interpreted very widely and suggests the criteria are largely at the Minister’s discretion. We believe that a stricter definition, which makes clear that only legislation which is effectively no longer in use, and has no practical effect, should be able to be subject to these powers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are also not persuaded that the existing safeguards to ensure parliamentary scrutiny of controversial uses of these powers are strong enough. In particular, we believe Select Committees could find it difficult to fully track and consider repeals, especially if these provisions are used regularly.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses 58-61 </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">- </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Exercise</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> of regulatory functions </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These clauses refer to the ‘growth duty’. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB supports compliant growth. It is a sensible idea that regulators have </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a duty to consider economic impact and growth as part of both their micro and macro decisions. This way compliant growth will be the aim of both individual regulators during their regulatory actions as well as part of the regulators</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> operational practices and procedures. The FSB supports the notion that this extra duty should not impact upon the way that they deal with serious non-compliance, that this duty should in fact complement existing duties.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Economic growth can be supported by regulators in a number of ways. They should be supporting growth through the provision of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">assured, reliable and easy to use </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">advice and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">support businesses to be compliant and efficient. They should also be proportionate in their actions and not place unnecessary barriers in the way of business growth. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Finally, we believe that any duty should be for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sustainable</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> economic growth, as otherwise this could include seeking economic growth measures without regard to the long-term viability of industries or business sectors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">To do this they should have a good understanding of how </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">small </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">businesses operate and where possible take positive actions such as booking inspections in advance, allow businesses to pay regulatory fees in a way that best suits them and their cash flow, and to ensure that there is a clear one stop shop for all necessary advice. Regulators should ensure that all staff </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">spe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> time to understand the way that small and micro businesses operate and create good working relationships with them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FSB supports compliant growth and believes that all regulators should also see this as their ultimate aim. There is a need to ensure that this duty fits well alongside existing duties and allows regulators to work c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">-operatively with businesses to achieve compliance but also deal with rogue traders where necessary. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Regulators should be supporters of better business. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">16 September 2013</span></p><p style="border-top-color:#d9d9d9; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> | </span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:3pt">Page</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>